what is faceted search and how does it work in tantivy?
Faceted search is a technique used in information retrieval systems to allow users to refine their search results by applying multiple filters based on different attributes (facets) of the data. These facets can include categories, tags, dates, ranges, and other metadata that help narrow down the search results to more relevant items.

### How Faceted Search Works

1. **Indexing**: During the indexing phase, documents are analyzed and indexed with various facets. For example, an e-commerce site might index products with facets like category, brand, price range, and customer ratings.

2. **Querying**: When a user performs a search, the system retrieves the initial set of results based on the query terms.

3. **Faceting**: The system then calculates the counts of documents that fall into each facet category within the search results. This allows users to see how many results match each facet and to further refine their search by selecting one or more facets.

4. **Filtering**: Users can apply these facet filters to narrow down the search results. The system updates the results and facet counts dynamically based on the selected filters.

### Faceted Search in Tantivy

[Tantivy](https://github.com/quickwit-oss/tantivy) is a full-text search engine library written in Rust. It is designed to be fast, reliable, and easy to use. Tantivy supports faceted search, allowing you to build powerful search applications with filtering capabilities.

#### Setting Up Faceted Search in Tantivy

1. **Define Schema**: When creating the schema for your index, you need to define the fields that will be used as facets. These fields should be indexed and stored.

    ```rust
    use tantivy::schema::*;

    let mut schema_builder = Schema::builder();
    schema_builder.add_text_field("title", TEXT | STORED);
    schema_builder.add_text_field("body", TEXT);
    schema_builder.add_facet_field("category");
    schema_builder.add_facet_field("brand");
    let schema = schema_builder.build();
    ```

2. **Indexing Documents**: When adding documents to the index, you need to include the facet fields.

    ```rust
    use tantivy::Index;
    use tantivy::schema::Facet;

    let index = Index::create_in_ram(schema.clone());
    let mut index_writer = index.writer(50_000_000)?;

    let mut doc = Document::default();
    doc.add_text(title, "The Great Gatsby");
    doc.add_text(body, "A novel written by American author F. Scott Fitzgerald.");
    doc.add_facet(category, Facet::from("/books/fiction"));
    doc.add_facet(brand, Facet::from("/brand/penguin"));

    index_writer.add_document(doc);
    index_writer.commit()?;
    ```

3. **Searching with Facets**: When performing a search, you can request facet counts and apply facet filters.

    ```rust
    use tantivy::query::QueryParser;
    use tantivy::collector::FacetCollector;
    use tantivy::collector::TopDocs;

    let reader = index.reader()?;
    let searcher = reader.searcher();

    let query_parser = QueryParser::for_index(&index, vec![title, body]);
    let query = query_parser.parse_query("Gatsby")?;

    let mut facet_collector = FacetCollector::for_field("category");
    facet_collector.add_facet("/books");

    let top_docs = searcher.search(&query, &(facet_collector, TopDocs::with_limit(10)))?;

    let facet_counts = facet_collector.facet_counts();
    for (facet, count) in facet_counts {
        println!("{}: {}", facet.to_path_string(), count);
    }

    for (score, doc_address) in top_docs {
        let retrieved_doc = searcher.doc(doc_address)?;
        println!("Document: {:?}", retrieved_doc);
    }
    ```

In this example, the `FacetCollector` is used to collect facet counts for the "category" field. The search results and facet counts are then printed out.

By using faceted search in Tantivy, you can build efficient and user-friendly search interfaces that allow users to refine their search results based on various attributes. This can greatly improve the search experience and help users find the information they are looking for more quickly and accurately.

